instructions.instructions: Give the meanings of the following signs and symptoms.

prompt.text: After a total (complete) hysterectomy, a woman still has regular menstrual periods.

readingPart.reading: False. Total hysterectomy means removal of the entire uterus so that menstruation does not occur.

prompt.text: After a total hysterectomy, a woman may still produce estrogen and progesterone.

readingPart.reading: True. Total hysterectomy does not mean that the ovaries have been removed.

prompt.text: Birth control pills prevent pregnancy by keeping levels of estrogen and progesterone high.

readingPart.reading: True. Birth control pills contain estrogen and progesterone; high levels prevent ovulation and pregnancy.

prompt.text: After a total hysterectomy with bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy, a doctor may advise hormone replacement therapy.

readingPart.reading: True. This may be necessary to treat symptoms of estrogen loss (vaginal atrophy, hot flashes) and to prevent bone deterioration (osteoporosis).

prompt.text: Human papillomavirus can cause genital warts and ovarian cancer.

readingPart.reading: False. HPV does produce genital warts but not ovarian cancer. In some cases, HPV infection may lead to cervical cancer.

prompt.text: A Pap test can detect cervical dysplasia.

readingPart.reading: True. A Pap test can detect abnormal changes in the cervix from cervical dysplasia to cervical intraepithelial neoplasia (CIN) and CIS (carcinoma in situ).

prompt.text: Human chorionic gonadotropin is produced by the ovaries during pregnancy.

readingPart.reading: False. The hormone hCG is produced by the placenta during pregnancy.

prompt.text: Gynecomastia is a common condition in pregnant women.

readingPart.reading: False. Gynecomastia is a condition of increased breast development in males .
False. Myomectomy means removal of muscle tumors (fibroids). Endometriosis is abnormal location of uterine tissue outside the uterine lining.

prompt.text: A gravida 3 para 2 is a woman who has given birth 3 times.

readingPart.reading: False. A gravida 3 para 2 is a woman who has had two children and three pregnancies.

prompt.text: A nulligravida is a woman who has had several pregnancies.

readingPart.reading: False. A nulligravida has had no pregnancies. A multigravida has had many pregnancies.

prompt.text: Pseudocyesis is the same condition as a tubal pregnancy.

readingPart.reading: False. A pseudocyesis is a false pregnancy (no pregnancy occurs), and a tubal pregnancy is an example of ectopic pregnancy (pregnancy occurs in the fallopian tube, not in the uterus).

prompt.text: Fibrocystic changes in the breast are a malignant condition.

readingPart.reading: False. Fibrocystic changes in the breast are a benign condition.
True. Cystadenomas are glandular sacs lined with tumor cells; they occur in the ovaries.
False. FSH and LH are pituitary gland hormones. Estrogen and progesterone are secreted by the ovaries.

questionContent.questionText:
1. malignant tumor of the ovary [cystadenocarcinoma]

2. inflammation in the lower, neck-like portion of the uterus [cervicitis]

3. condition during pregnancy or shortly thereafter, marked by hypertension, proteinuria, and edema [preeclampsia]

4. uterine tissue located outside the uterus—for example, in the ovaries, cul-de-sac, fallopian tubes, or peritoneum [endometriosis]

5. premature separation of a normally implanted placenta [abruptio placentae]

6. placenta implantation over the cervical opening [placenta previa]

7. more than one fetus inside the uterus [multiple gestations]

8. malignant condition of the lower portion of the uterus [cervical cancer]

9. malignant condition of the inner lining of the uterus [endometrial cancer]

10. benign muscle tumor in the uterus [leiomyoma]

instructions.instructions: Match the listed terms with the meanings/descriptions that follow.

questionContent.questionText:
1. Burning of abnormal tissue with chemicals or an electrically heated instrument: [cauterization]

2. Contrast material is injected into the uterus and fallopian tubes, and x-ray images are obtained: [hysterosalpingography]

3. Cold temperature is used to destroy tissue: [cryosurgery/cryocauterization]

4. Visual examination of the vagina and cervix: [colposcopy]

5. Widening the cervical opening and scraping the lining of the uterus: [dilation and curettage/dilatation and curettage/dilation & curettage]

6. Withdrawal of fluid or tissue from a cyst or solid mass by suction with a needle: [fine needle aspiration]

7. Process of recording x-ray images of the breast: [mammography]

8. Removal of a cone-shaped section of the cervix for diagnosis or treatment of cervical dysplasia: [conization]

9. Surgical puncture to remove fluid from the cul-de-sac: [culdocentesis]

10. Echoes from sound waves create an image of structures in the pelvic region: [pelvic ultrasonography]

11. Blocking the fallopian tubes to prevent fertilization from occurring: [tubal ligation]

12. Visual examination of the abdominal cavity with an endoscope: [laparoscopy]

13. hCG is measured in the urine or blood: [pregnancy test]

14. Cells are scraped from the cervix or vagina for microscopic analysis: [Pap test]

15. Removal of internal gynecologic organs and adjacent structures in the pelvis: [pelvic exenteration]

questionContent.questionText:
1. Dr. Hanson felt that it was important to do a [Pap test/culdocentesis/amniocentesis] once yearly on each of her GYN patients to screen for abnormal cells.

2. When Doris missed her period, her doctor checked for the presence of [hCG/LH/IUD] in Doris ’ s urine to see if she was pregnant.

3. Ellen was 34 weeks pregnant and experiencing bad headaches and blurry vision, with a 10-pound weight gain in 2 days. Dr. Murphy told her to go to the obstetric emergency department because she suspected [preeclampsia/pelvic inflammatory disease/fibroids].

4. Fifty-two-year-old Sally noticed increasing pain, fullness, and swelling in her abdomen. She had a history of ovarian cancer, so her physician recommended [pelvic ultrasonography/colposcopy/sentinel node biopsy].

5. Clara knew that she should not ignore her fevers and yellow vaginal discharge and the pain in her side. She had previous episodes of [PID/PMS/HRT] treated with IV antibiotics. She worried that she might have a recurrence.

6. After years of trying to become pregnant, Jill decided to speak to her [gynecologist/hematologist/urologist] about in vitro [fertilization/gestation/parturition].

7. To harvest her ova, Jill’s physician prescribed hormones to stimulate egg maturation and [ovulation/coitus/lactation]. Ova were surgically removed and fertilized with sperm cells in a Petri dish.

8. Next, multiple embryos were implanted into Jill’s [uterus/fallopian tube/vagina], and she received hormones to ensure the survival of at least one embryo.

9. The IVF was successful and after [ultrasound examination/abdominal CT], Jill was told that she would have twins in 81/2 months.

10. At 37 weeks, Jill went into labor. Under continuous [fetal monitoring/chorionic villus sampling/culdocentesis], two healthy infants were delivered vaginally.

11. At age 41, Carol had a screening [mammogram/hysterosalpingogram/conization] of her breasts. The results showed tiny calcium deposits, or calcifications, behind her [areola/chorion/adnexa uteri]. A core needle [biopsy/laparoscopy/colposcopy] was performed and showed cells that were an early sign of cancer called [DCIS/CIN/DUB]. Her surgical oncologist recommended [lumpectomy/TAH-BSO/chorionic villus sampling] to remove the calcifications and surrounding tissue as treatment.
